The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 24, 2004 				 Panel to iron out allotment glitches
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 Nayak: The problem solver																								Mumbai, April 23: With foreign institutional investors like Calpers eyeing India as an investment destination, the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) is anxious to avoid aberrations like the ONGC and Power Trading share allotment fiascos.																								The market regulator today constituted a high-level taskforce, headed by UTI Bank chief P. J. Nayak, to carry out a thorough health-check on securities market infrastructure covering segments like equities and players, including exchanges, and recommend ways to upgrade facilities and skills of system.																								The 13-member panel would review infrastructure, diagnose the deficiencies, inadequacies and recommend solutions to upgrade facilities, standards and skills, Sebi said in a statement. 																								The regulator endeavours to match the growth potential of the economy and anticipated rise in volumes in securities transactions and multiplicity of products.																								The taskforce would also recommend the best practices to set up, maintain and upgrade infrastructure, both hardware and software. It would also advise on business continuity plans.																								The group would also look into scalability of infrastructure and skills to introduce diversification in products like commodities and foreign exchange, it said, adding the mandate includes recommending solutions for seamless and secure technological interface for transaction processing. The taskforce would recommend appropriate delineation of role and obligation of the market participants, it said. 
